Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California at Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical uniformities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will make it possible to search for related stars among the stars, that is, those that have arisen from the same cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and a brief summary of them can be found on the university website.
The reason for the similar chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in the gas clouds that precedes the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the stellar cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of relative stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical abundance from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of simulations carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, the researchers used a supercomputer to simulate two flows of interstellar gas, which together formed a cloud.
This object over several million years, under the influence of its own gravity, is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added paint markers to the initial gas streams and found that a high degree of chemical uniformity was achieved due to the rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to search for relative stars by chemical composition, as well as determine possible regions for the formation of such objects.
