Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill that would protect unionization as a civil right.
&quot;Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs,&quot; says Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat who co-chairs the Congressional Progressive Caucus.
That&#39;s why I&#39;m proud to present the Workers Empowerment Act, along with civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal options to discriminate against union organizing as they do to other forms of discrimination, stopping anti-union forces
Changing the Labor Relations Act to allow workers who face discrimination for organizing unions to seek justice in civil courts - and receive damages and penalties - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the bill&#39;s co-sponsors are proposing is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that unions have come under in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country pass a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Tojo&#39;s paramilitary autocracy was replaced by a democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions have a role to play in shaping the new Japan, they included text that explicitly recognized that &quot;the right of workers to organize and to negotiate and to act collectively is guaranteed.&quot;
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler&#39;s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that explicitly stated: &quot;The right to form associations for the purpose of protecting and improving working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe on this right will be null and void; measures aimed at these purposes will be recognized as illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chair of the International Commission on Human Rights that drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which in 1948 would be adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that &quot;everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect their interests.&quot;
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and for this union to participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions, the unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack the unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, as we should.
The formal recognition of labor rights as human rights - and the expansion of civil rights protections to prevent discrimination against union organizing - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are resurrecting the ideals that historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge temporarily blocks legislation that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the US, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the passage of a Louisiana law that its supporters say would likely close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under the measure, signed into law by Louisiana Gov. Bobby Ginadle in June and due to take effect September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have admittance to hospitals within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge&#39;s decision means doctors can continue to perform legal abortions for the time being while continuing to seek such authority.
&quot;Plaintiffs will be allowed to operate legally while continuing to act to obtain credentials,&quot; Judge John deGravells wrote in his decision.
A hearing will be scheduled within the month in which the judge makes a more permanent ruling on this law.
Abortion rights advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a string of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital credentials.
&quot;Today&#39;s decision ensures that Louisiana women are protected from a treacherous law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,&quot; said Nancy Northup, president and director of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of five state clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to physicians from two clinics who were not plaintiffs in this case and also applied for admittance authority.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed such laws, and courts have recently found such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would shut down most of the state&#39;s remaining clinics were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion rights activists, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admissions laws place restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are intended to protect women&#39;s health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admissions authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all the other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing the procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing the procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not penalize abortion doctors as long as their applications for admissions authority are pending.
What will the introduction of quotas on domestic products lead to?
At least half of the products for each type of product in the assortment of retail chains should be Russian-made, said Oleg Nilov, State Duma deputy from the Just Russia faction.
The parliamentarian has prepared a draft law aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, the Izvestia newspaper writes.
The document will still be detailed in order to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. &lt;...&gt; For the rest of the product groups that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic manufacturers,&quot; Nilov told the publication.
Together with the amendments to the article &quot;On the Fundamentals of State Regulation of Trading Activities in the Russian Federation&quot;, the draft law provides for amendments to the Tax Code, establishing a reduced VAT rate of 10% for the sale of products manufactured in Russia.
The idea to introduce a 50% quota in retail chains is included in the stimulus package for Russian manufacturers.
Several times more domestic goods will appear on the shelves.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to the lawyer of the company &quot;Nalogovik&quot;, a member of the independent expert center &quot;Public Duma&quot; Sergei Litvinenko, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive and will lead to growth.
In the black will be agricultural producers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that profits will grow.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate their terms and prices to retailers, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian manufacturers will be able to scale up their operations and sales, which will result in higher taxes being paid than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will begin to expand, some will develop faster, and will contribute to GDP growth.
Russia&#39;s dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, though not immediately,&quot; the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not break into local stores due to high competition from foreign counterparts.
Now, after the introduction of the embargo, this niche has been vacated and we can breathe a sigh of relief.
But do not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary checks, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, now there is a &quot;moment of calm&quot; when the old players have already left, and the new ones have not yet arrived.
Almost a month later, we can talk about an increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as an increase in prices for finished products,&quot; said Tamara Kasyanova, First Vice-President of the all-Russian public organization &quot;Russian Club of Financial Directors&quot;, Ph.
Definitely, the idea to sell at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow the sector to be secured to local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that are cheaper due to subsidies from another state.
In other words, the struggle for the buyer will unfold between companies operating under the same laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian manufacturers are far from being able to satisfy 50% of their compatriots&#39; domestic needs in all respects.
And in this situation, retail chains will have to &quot;reach out&quot; the share of Russian goods to half of the assortment.
In this regard, fears are growing that low-quality goods will arrive on the shelves.
It is possible that foreign products with broken labels will be supplied under the guise of those produced in Russia,&quot; the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large retail chains, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that in this situation, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, since the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not exclude that the law on quotas for domestic goods may also affect consumers.
The fact is that some Russian-made products may be inferior in quality to imported counterparts, while stores will be able to raise prices for the latter, as for a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, forgotten in the early 2000s, was again discussed by economists in February of this year due to the ongoing devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the backdrop of difficult relations with the West, the issue of refusing imported products is becoming even more relevant.
The law is intended to oblige retailers to take into account domestic manufacturers when placing orders with suppliers.
Then we will follow the path of import substitution much faster and more confidently, and the production planning system for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time,&quot; MP Oleg Nilov says.
The quota mechanism will be especially effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is especially high, for example, in the dairy industry, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really capable of completely covering the shelves of Russian stores.
In addition, meat production can also receive a powerful impetus.
As you know, the largest share of imports remains for beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% still falls on Russian products,&quot; Kasyanova argues.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and may accelerate this process.
However, by itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, since this requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be imported from abroad, which means that full-fledged import substitution will not occur, but significant steps will be taken in this direction.
In addition, it is not enough to set quotas; it is also necessary to organize the production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas will provide just such guarantees,&quot; the expert states.
Late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean more ovarian cancer kills more in rural areas
Angelina Jolie and her brother James have posted a video in memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who forgive in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those who live in cities.
The researchers analyzed the charts of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that just 35 percent lived five years after they were diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research said that those who live in the regions and outlying areas of the state are 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who live in urban areas.
SMALL STUDY: New Drugs May Slow Lung and Ovarian Cancer
The researchers followed the women&#39;s medical path for seven years.
Dr. Jordan said a woman&#39;s age at diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, current medical conditions, and socioeconomic status also affected survival.
Older women and those with advanced cancer at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
Those who lived in regions or outlying areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who lived in urban areas.
While the study was not intended to determine why women who live outside cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
&quot;This disease is best treated by surgeons who specialize in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in big cities,&quot; she said.
While improving telehealth services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing outreach services to allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people receiving treatment away from home, could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer funded study will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Niv, was told that she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
