Inflation is out of the holiday.
Will the Russians feel a sharp rise in prices
As a result of cross-sanctions of the Russian Federation and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not meet the forecasts of the authorities, analysts at VTB Capital are convinced.
According to experts, the delayed consequences of anti-sanctions will lead to an inflationary shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, and even less next year - 6.5%.
However, according to the Kommersant newspaper, this week the Ministry of Economic Development should make &quot;small but fundamental&quot; adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast until 2017.
According to the publication, the agency may lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zeroing of income growth.
The forecast assumed that Russia&#39;s food sanctions would be in effect for a year, until August 2015.
How could such high inflation be expected in such a situation?
The current situation suggests a one-time shock, but the downward trend in inflation will not change,&quot; a source in the Finance Ministry said.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the financial and economic bloc of the government regarding inflation and forecast price growth in 2014 at the level of 8%.
The main effect of food bans will come along with the possible introduction of a sales tax (NSP) in the regions of the Russian Federation in 2015, experts are convinced.
Inflation will peak at 9% in February, after which the annual rate of price growth will decline, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflation results after the Russian Federation introduced &quot;neat sanctions.&quot;
AiF.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, head of the analytical department of AForex FC:
The rise in prices is already observed in the main segments of goods.
Moreover, when socially important products began to rise in price, the government was forced to launch systematic monitoring of price stability in order to prevent the risks of unreasonable price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting on a daily basis to regulators so that the authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason initiate price increases.
The key factors in the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the colossal rate of capital outflow, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, internal conversion due to the flight of the population into foreign currency, as well as an embargo on the import of food products from countries that have joined the sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures had been kept under control, the cost of the minimum basket of food would not have jumped 12% in just one quarter.
The ban on the import of food products provoked a supply shock in the domestic market and led to a completely logical increase in the final cost.
Since at the current stage we are unable to fully launch the import substitution mechanism, as well as increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to bear the risks of an increase in the inflationary component.
If we add here the fiscal reasons associated with the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the worsened prospects for economic growth, inflation could well exceed 8% by the end of this year.
Alexander Razuvaev, director of the analytical department of Alpari
In the 1990s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, in the 2000s it was also higher than the current level, but it is another matter that at that time this was compensated by rapid economic growth.
I think that by the end of the year inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Platon Maguta, Asset Manager of Managing Company &quot;Maguta Fund&quot;
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia has been successfully contained so far, but if there is a further increase in pressure, primarily on the financial sector, this may lead to certain difficulties and increase inflationary expectations of the population, which usually traditionally manifest themselves in purchases of cash currency in order to to secure your savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the gradual weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and by state regulation.
But the rise in prices traditionally begins after the summer lull and, perhaps, this fall will become more noticeable.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia at 7.5% is likely to survive, since the Russian Federation still has financial savings.
