Biggest Chinese Companies Team Up Against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China&#39;s largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (social media, messenger, etc.) and Baidu (China&#39;s largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
However, catching up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which has left even its American rivals eBay and Amazon.com behind, will not be easy.
Union of the largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will be owned by Wanda and 15% by each of the Internet companies, the Wanda Group said in a statement.
It is planned to register a company in Hong Kong.
The JV will combine Baidu&#39;s search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China with about 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, the Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial properties across China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $8 billion) to build a film studio and theme park in Qingdao, a city in eastern China on the shores of the Yellow Sea.
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and bring in $960 million in revenue.
In addition, Wanda owns the American cinema chain AMC Entertainment Holdings, making the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all of its malls, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, the development of which will be developed by the emerging rival Alibaba.
Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year, according to Dong Ce, who will lead the new company.
The new site should become the world&#39;s largest online-to-offline platform, said Dong Ce.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers on the Internet so that they come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
Coupon services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru are a classic example of O2O.
&quot;O2O is the biggest pie in online commerce,&quot; said Wanda CEO Wang Jianlin (Bloomberg cited).
&quot;Currently, there is no real O2O platform in China, and in this situation, everyone&#39;s chances are approximately equal,&quot; he said.
China&#39;s e-commerce market is the largest in the world and McKinsey &amp; Co. estimates it will more than triple by 2015 from 2011 to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has grown to 632 million, Bloomberg cites official statistics: this is more than the population of any country in the world, with the exception of India.
And according to forecasts, by 2015 this number could grow to 850 million people.
Union of the richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huateng was China&#39;s richest man until recently, but according to the Bloomberg Millionaires Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already surpassed him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma&#39;s net worth is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion comes from his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu chief Robin Li is now the third richest person in China, while Wanda&#39;s Wang Jianlin is fourth.
&quot;This battle is very exciting to watch as the three richest people join forces to challenge the even richer,&quot; Cao Lei, director of China&#39;s Hangzhou e-commerce research center, told Bloomberg.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after the creation: &quot;Rome cannot be built in one day.&quot;
The fact that it is not so easy to compete with Alibaba not only for new companies, but also for the deserved leaders of global e-commerce, is evidenced by the report on Alibaba&#39;s financial performance for the last quarter, published the day before.
Alibaba is often described as a cross between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June, the Chinese company earned more than both of its US rivals combined.
Alibaba&#39;s net income for the period is almost double that of its peers, up nearly three times year-on-year to $1.99 billion.
&quot;Alibaba still has huge potential for generating money, thanks in large part to its mobile apps,&quot; an analyst at Hong Kong&#39;s Arete Research Service told Bloomberg.
According to Alibaba&#39;s updated prospectus on the US Securities and Exchange Commission website, the number of active mobile users of the company&#39;s services in July was 188 million, which significantly exceeds the March figure of 163 million people.
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the past quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba will have to name the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to the average estimate of 11 analysts polled by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the sale of shares.
Alibaba&#39;s debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) could take place as early as September 16, according to Bloomberg sources.
The road-show of the company preceding this event starts on September 3rd.
Alibaba&#39;s IPO is expected to be a record in the history of the NYSE and will allow the company to raise about $20 billion.
Until now, the record for the volume of funds raised on the US exchanges belonged to the Visa payment system, which in 2008 held an initial public offering of its shares, earning $17.9 billion from it.
