How people live in the oldest house in Ufa
There are 18 apartments in the former house of gold miners and miners Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on October Revolution Street 57/1 (formerly Bolshaya Kazanskaya).
The house of the 18th century has not changed much since its construction, except for dilapidation.
Outsiders go here as if on a tour, and the residents suffer more than they rejoice from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Ufa house, the walls of which remember the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is inaccurate, historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But in any case, it turns out that the building is almost 300 years old.
An old courtyard, an always open door, a creaky staircase.
The doors to the apartments are located close to each other, the walls are cracked, and the street is visible in places through the gaps from the peeling plaster.
Everything seems to be based on honesty.
And the locals assure: &quot;Don&#39;t you think it&#39;s true.&quot;
Living in an 18th-century wooden house is very difficult, says Tatyana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment No. 3.
The object is under state protection, but no money has been allocated for its maintenance for decades, and we feel like museum pieces that the authorities have simply forgotten about.
The last renovation was 40 years ago.
The walls are still somehow holding up, but the foundation is all rotten.
Many residents still go to the toilet outside and wash themselves once a week in a public bath.
How can you be satisfied in such conditions?!
The road passes right under the windows, there is not even a pedestrian zone.
Tatyana pushes back the curtain.
Now you can see what was only audible before: a stream of cars rushing under the windows.
You see, the windows rattle all the time, we can’t open the windows, but we’re used to the noise.
A person gets used to everything, good and bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
Moreover, we have two rooms, the three of us live with our son.
And other families have much worse conditions; on the second floor, the ceilings are generally a little more than one and a half meters high.
For contrast, Tatiana offers to visit her neighbor from apartment No. 6, Lyudmila Starostina.
A pleasant hospitable woman from the doorway offers a cup of coffee and says with a sad smile:
We have a one-room apartment, 14.5 m² for four people, and we live like this: my husband and I and my daughter and granddaughter.
I have been here since birth, there has never been another living space, - Lyudmila looks around the room: mezzanines, two sofas with the letter &quot;g&quot;; on one of them is a granddaughter with a laptop.
Very crowded and not much different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, &quot;historical&quot;.
But it regularly flows from the ceiling: the plumbing system is no good.
Lyudmila talks about her apartment in a casual and surprising way, like an Italian whose house stands on Roman ruins.
That is, it reduces into one very old and recent, everyday and legendary:
The water supply was carried out about 40 years ago during the last repair.
Then they made us a small kitchen in a nook and a toilet from a former closet.
We live just where Demidov and his family lodged, servants lived on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
The Ufa Real Estate Center says that privatization does not matter.
All the same, we will get only a one-room apartment, we cannot claim more.
Already four months ago they promised to resettle us, but things did not go further than promises.
I&#39;m not used to complaining and I won&#39;t.
A whole dynasty lived in this apartment (room!): my grandparents, mom and dad, me and my husband, and my daughter and granddaughter.
Everything happened during this time.
For example, hefty rats ran around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the wing, they are a meter thick!
They say the solution was mixed with eggs, which is why it lasts so long.
The house was built thoroughly, thanks to the Demidovs!
This is probably the only reason so far no one has been killed by a collapsed ceiling or pile.
Only the building is still slowly dying before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house are rotting, the floors have repeatedly failed, we poured cement, but everything is useless - the solution goes into the ground, like into a well.
They say it is - under our room there is a secret hole and a passage to the Belaya River, which the Old Believers who once lived here specially made so that they could hide from danger, in which case.
They were being pursued.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them and begged them to let him start excavations in the apartment.
And then he urged them to give them a living space in exchange for his odnushka on October Avenue.
Lyudmila refused the historian:
Where are we four in one?
And here there is at least a tiny hope that they will give more spacious housing.
If we had agreed to the exchange, we would not have won anything.
However, the Starostin family did not win anything.
Lyudmila&#39;s biggest dream is to be resettled, and her daughter and her 16-year-old granddaughter are given a separate room.
That is, two families were allocated a two-room apartment instead of not the most majestic ruins in which two generations live now.
Pretty, petite girl Olesya Karsakova from apartments No. 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, in two cramped little rooms with a total area of 23 m², called apartments, her large family lives.
There are seven of us, two children.
You can see for yourself what the conditions are.
The plaster is falling off in pieces, as are the window frames, there are through holes in the walls in the kitchen and in the rooms.
The tap water is cold all year round.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest house in Ufa, you can see that the Lavrentievs from apartment No. 4 were the most fortunate.
They occupy the most spacious rooms on the ground floor.
You are right, there are many places!
The room is 75 squares, three people are registered.
We live just in those rooms where, according to legend, Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family, Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentiev.
The ceilings are high and spacious.
One thing is bad - everything around is bursting at the seams, falling apart, collapsing.
The neighbors must have already told you!
We have the most torment with the floors: the wooden boards rotted, the earth literally left from under our feet.
I put props, wedges; there is nothing in the hall yet, but in the other room we walk, as if we are swinging on a swing, everything is so shaky.
Alexander Dmitrievich can tell about the house of the merchant Evdokim Demidov better than any guide.
He treats the gold miner as if he were his own, speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was outstanding: the owner of the Kaginsky and Uzyansky factories built houses, cast cannons and bells, and kept the Ural mines.
The heirs of merchant real estate are proud of their ancestor, but they no longer want to live under the same roof with history.
I settled here as a child, in the 40s of the XX century, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
Then there were wooden carriages, stables and guard houses around, which were later demolished.
In 1968, they also wanted to clean our house, but something got in the way ...
History repeated itself in 2014: again they beckoned with new housing.
We, as if on command, collected all the documents, ran around the necessary authorities, and suddenly found out that the move to the apartments was postponed to 2015 or 2016.
We don&#39;t believe in any of this anymore...
Two years ago, Lavrentiev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to find out about the fate of the house.
Officials did not accept the tenant.
They sent them from one table to another, and then, as if in mockery, they gave out a piece of paper without a signature and a seal: &quot;The Ministry of Culture has no objection to the resettlement of the tenants.&quot;
I even got the feeling that our house has long been gone from the city plan, because at first it was number 57, then it became 57 A, and now 57/1.
Looks like it was demolished in the 70s.
&quot;Russian Planet&quot; turned to the head of the sector of information and analytical work of the Department of Land Resources of Ufa, Vladimir Barabash.
The house on October Revolution Street 57/1 is included in the program for the resettlement of dilapidated housing.
I cannot be responsible for the actions of the officials of the 70s, I only know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all the old houses, despite the historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities - to restore all the old houses on October Revolution Street, which are of architectural value - is being successfully implemented.
Residents will soon be resettled in new apartments.
According to Barabash, the Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice will restore the Demidov House.
Now an architectural biennale is taking place in Italy, and the project &quot;Old Ufa&quot; is presented there among others.
