From her point of view, black women are in a position to clearly share these issues; they face complex realities every day.
While white women are now integrating issues of race and gender into the feminist mainstream, Angela Hattery, a professor of women&#39;s and gender studies at George Mason University, says their predecessors did the opposite.
&quot;Between 1865 and 1890, at least 10,000 black men were lynched, and the basis for this was almost always the rape of a white woman,&quot; Hattery said.
It needed a white woman to corroborate the story to justify the lynching.
From Hattery&#39;s point of view, the gap between white and black women occurred when white suffragettes like Susan B. Anthony looked into the situation in the late 1800s and saw that the fight for suffrage would only be effective for one of the groups: women or blacks. .
&quot;They made the decision to put all their eggs in the women&#39;s voting rights basket, and black voting rights would come later,&quot; Hattery said.
Looking back at things like this gives us a clear idea of why women of color don&#39;t trust white women.
We didn&#39;t do anything good.
We have never helped black women protect their husbands and sons.
Even after women won the vote in 1920, it took ten years for white women to organize against lynchings into the Southern Women&#39;s Association to Prevent Lynchings.
The group comes almost 40 years after black women first asked for help, Mitchell said.
From Mitchell&#39;s point of view, the rise in white feminist reactions to the issues raised by the Ferguson situation - police behavior, racial discrimination - reflects a time when white feminists had to &quot;catch up&quot; with issues that black women had dealt with for generations.
&quot;Wouldn&#39;t it be great if activists who have this [traditional feminist] ideology would take the right to raise a child as seriously as they take the right to contraception?&quot; Mitchell asked.
Second-wave feminists who made careers fighting for reproductive rights and access to contraceptives are now beginning to understand what that means.
Prominent white feminist activist Gloria Steinem, two weeks after Michael Brown&#39;s assassination, took to Facebook to post a scathing op-ed by Guardian columnist Rebecca Carroll demanding that white Americans become more involved in protests over racism.
&quot;I hope women who have a different but similar reason to understand the dangers of the body - and perspectives on racial issues that differ significantly in public opinion polls - will lead the change,&quot; Steinem wrote.
While Steinem vouches for a more cross-cutting feminism that includes both racial and gender issues, her comments about race in America still surprise some.
American Enterprise Institute researcher Christina Sommers, author of Who Stole Feminism?, told She The People that young men in the United States, especially young people of color, are &quot;much more vulnerable than their sisters,&quot; but Steinem&#39;s remarks about Ferguson contradict criticism. which she had previously expressed.
Now we have hundreds of special programs for girls and young women, but almost nothing for boys.
However, when the White House recently initiated a small program, My Brother&#39;s Watchman, to help vulnerable black and Hispanic youth, there was an outcry from many feminists, including Gloria Steinem.
Police relations with the black community are not the only issues pushing the front lines of traditional feminism.
After the US Border Patrol arrested some 63,000 unaccompanied minors on the country&#39;s southwestern border this year, immigration reform has resurfaced - this time as a women&#39;s issue.
