The Ministry of Economic Development wants to accelerate the growth of the electric car market
This week, the Ministry of Economic Development will submit to the government a comprehensive plan for the development of environmentally friendly transport in Russia, said Oleg Pluzhnikov, deputy director of the department of the ministry, at a round table held by Vedomosti at the Moscow Motor Show - 2014.
The plan was drawn up on behalf of the government, one of the main goals is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
The document is expected to be adopted in late September - early October, says Pluzhnikov, the proposed measures relate to electric vehicles and hybrids - a plan for the development of vehicles running on natural gas fuel in Russia already exists.
The plan (Vedomosti has a copy) is designed for 2014-2017.
Evaluation criteria for electric and hybrid vehicles are to be developed and how to encourage the use and production of environmentally friendly vehicles.
A report to the government describing tax and customs measures to support electric transport will be ready by December 2014; the preferential lending and preferential leasing scheme will appear by April 2015; and proposals to reduce the price of machines, stimulate localization and create a service infrastructure will be developed by October 2015.
In 2014-2015 it is planned to amend the regulations to facilitate the construction of charging infrastructure (in parking lots, gas stations, etc.).
In addition, federal officials intend during 2015 to formulate proposals for regional authorities to also stimulate the use of environmentally friendly transport - in the form of providing it with advantages in driving and parking, for example; and by February 2016 - and proposals to expand public procurement of such vehicles.
Finally, by October 2014 the Ministry of Economic Development will add to the list of indicators for evaluating the activities of regional authorities criteria that reflect the effectiveness of supporting the production of environmentally friendly vehicles, the development of charging infrastructure.
The market for electric vehicles in Russia is just being formed - in 2013, about 100 electric vehicles were sold throughout the country.
At the beginning of 2014, the import duty on electric vehicles was reset to zero, so sales will amount to about 500 units, Andrey Pankov, CEO of Mitsubishi Motors in Russia, predicts.
But even a five-fold increase does not make electric vehicles any noticeable: in 2013, according to the Association of European Businesses, 2.78 million cars and light commercial vehicles were sold in Russia.
So far, only Mitsubishi Motors imports electric vehicles to Russia.
Renault is preparing to start importing - the company focuses primarily on corporate clients, says Nicolas Remis, director of strategic planning and partnerships for Renault in Russia.
The majority of other manufacturers of electric transport took a wait-and-see attitude towards Russia.
Russian manufacturers also have developments of electric vehicles - &quot;&quot;, GAZ, &quot;&quot;, but the output is scanty.
For example, in January-July 2014, according to ACM Holding, AvtoVAZ produced 30 electric vehicles.
Demand is low due to the high cost of electric vehicles, AvtoVAZ director for engineering Sergei Amanov admits, there will be no breakthrough in this segment without state support....
The development of the Russian market of electric vehicles, in addition to the high cost of cars (the electric vehicles that are sold in Russia, on average, are twice as expensive as their counterparts with internal combustion engines), is constrained by the underdevelopment of the charging infrastructure (gas stations - a few), sighs Avtostat CEO Sergey Tselikov.
Due to the high cost and low rates of cost reduction, electric vehicles will remain a niche segment of the Russian market in the next 3-4 years, Mikhail Podorozhansky, editor-in-chief of Autoreview, predicts, Tselikov agrees with him.
Automakers, by contrast, say some EV models are already close to the cost of conventional ones.
The Russian market for electric vehicles has good prospects, the main thing is to instill confidence in consumers that &quot;electromobility&quot; is real; this, in particular, will be facilitated by the emergence of more and more charging stations, emphasizes the president of the BMW Group in Russia, Wolfgang Schlimme.
Such infrastructure projects are being implemented, for example, by the state company Rosseti: several stations have been built in Moscow, and about 80 more will soon appear.
Negotiations on the construction of a network of filling stations are also underway with other regions.
According to Vladimir Sofyin, director of the Rosseti department, the company believes in the electric car market and is ready to build filling stations throughout the country, but there are also problems: a small number of electric cars in the country and the lack of a single standard for charging electric cars of various brands.
In addition, Rosseti, as a grid company, does not have the right to engage in the sale of electricity, the possibility of doing this in relation to charging electric vehicles is being explored.
Pankov believes that the most effective measure of state support for the formation of an electric car market in Russia is the zeroing of customs duties.
The zero rate will be valid until the end of 2014, the possibility of its extension, expansion of the preferential list is being considered.
Replacing the transport tax with an environmental tax (the idea is being discussed and applies to all cars) will also support the market, but not as tangibly as customs preferences, Pankov believes.
The vehicle tax in Russia is low, says Pankov, unlike in Norway, for example, where tax cuts have boosted sales of electric vehicles, which now account for 12% of the market.
Russia also needs incentive measures for car owners, such as free parking in the city center (as they have already done in Moscow), Pankov is sure, or the possibility of moving electric vehicles along dedicated lanes, which is not yet available in Russia.
