Genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
The Briton said she spent many years thinking she was going to die after being misdiagnosed.
Caryn Rogers spent much of her teenage years thinking she only had a few years left to live after she was diagnosed with another medical condition.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT), a group of hereditary disorders that cause damage to nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because so little is known about the condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have CMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, unsteady gait and tucked toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, meaning that the symptoms get worse over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich&#39;s ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be wheelchair-bound by the time she was 18 and would die before she was 30.
The mother of two, now 51, said: &quot;As a child, I knew I couldn&#39;t do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me longer to do everything.
I could never roller skate or skateboard with other kids and was bullied a lot at school for the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to free her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at her medical record when her doctor left the room and it said she had AF.
&quot;I felt guilty because I stuck my nose where it shouldn&#39;t and so I didn&#39;t tell anyone, but I went back home and found information about the condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association,&quot; she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic possible.
I thought that I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in between.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk hadn&#39;t deteriorated as much as she thought and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up and hugged me and said, &quot;My dear, I don&#39;t think you have this disease because you would be in a wheelchair by now.&quot;
I think you have something that poses a much lesser threat to life.
After several genetic tests, she was found to have CMT.
&quot;When he explained what CMT was, I thought I had drawn a lucky ticket,&quot; she said.
The UK charity CMT has launched CMT Awareness Month to try to raise awareness of the disease.
Tax Burden on Washington Zone Entrepreneurs Grows as Economy Recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and more jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country increased modestly last year as the economic recovery accelerated, according to new research released last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid out $27.6 billion to state and local treasuries in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion they raised in 2012.
The state and local business tax burden increased 4.3 percent last year to $671 billion from 3.9 percent a year earlier, marking the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years in which bills decreased in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose faster, 4.3 percent, than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study by professional services firm Ernst &amp; Young and the Center for State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county&#39;s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from business taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland&#39;s tax revenue comes from businesses.
Virginia, at 28 percent, generates the least amount of tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
Much of the increase in tax revenue is driven by a rebound in property values for companies, researchers say, which has raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three straight years of less than 1 percent growth.
While large states such as California, New York, and Texas account for a large proportion of these receipts, the same appears to be happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, up $9.6 billion from 2012 - up 4.2 percent from the previous year.
However, the observed return of value to real estate does not have any similar effect on the growth of state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of company tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
&quot;What&#39;s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is either owned by the government or by non-profit organizations that don&#39;t pay property taxes,&quot; said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Taxation Center.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to pay for the same services that other states have.
The recent rise in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery in the real estate market.
Entrepreneurial incomes also seem to be on the mend, according to the data.
Companies in the region filed a $2.3 billion statewide corporate income tax, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although the trends are in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three localities.
Growth in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average, 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, at 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia saw a below-average rise in tax revenues of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate), at 6 percent.
Maryland has a corporate rate of 8.25 percent, while the county has a relatively high rate of 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the US Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower state and local business taxes and an overall more favorable business tax climate than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbor to the south.
North Carolina recently signed legislation to cut its corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, the same as Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to hit its tax revenue targets next year, this law could push the business income tax rate as high as 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be doing better and thus paying more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Entrepreneurial taxes paid in the form of personal income tax by small business owners - a transitional structure that most small firms are structured on - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, at a much faster rate of growth. than taxes for entrepreneurs in general.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with state and local government sales tax receipts up 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014. compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may be lagging behind as federal spending cuts weigh on the labor market in the region.
