Deputies proposed to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative is successful, the data of Russians cannot be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
A draft law has been submitted to the State Duma, providing for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is placed in the database of the legislative activity of the lower house.
Its authors were State Duma deputies Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov (United Russia), Vladimir Parakhin (Fair Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more efficient and effective provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the safety of personal data and respect for the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is being rushed by parliamentarians, obliges to store on the territory of the Russian Federation the personal data of Russians processed via the Internet.
It also makes mandatory the recording, systematization, accumulation, storage, clarification and extraction of personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as indicating information about the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right, based on a court decision, to restrict access to information processed in violation of Russian legislation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called &quot;black lists&quot; of violating sites - an automated information system &quot;Register of Violators of the Rights of Personal Data Subjects&quot;.
This law was adopted by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin from the Liberal Democratic Party and Alexander Yushchenko from the Communist Party.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill to postpone the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in the Russian Federation will have to pay rent
Commenting on the bill submitted today to the State Duma, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy, Leonid Levin, said that he sees no problems in postponing the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own storages of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation will be able to rent them, for example, &quot;from Rostelecom&quot;, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and is already providing its servers, from the Mail Group, from Western companies that are already providing their servers today.&quot;
&quot;In addition, there are several independent data centers that are ready to cooperate in this area,&quot; he added.
&quot;If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problem - they will receive technological opportunities for placement,&quot; Levin summed up.
controversial bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association for Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill was passed, Russians would no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services for air tickets and hotels.
According to the association, &quot;the bill deprives personal data subjects - citizens of the Russian Federation of the right to dispose of their own data, imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation.&quot;
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism for informing the user about where the recording is being made, systematizing his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose in which territory the specified actions will be carried out.
The adoption of similar bills on the &quot;localization&quot; of personal data in other countries led to the departure of global services and significant economic losses.
