Tricky Ways to Save Money on University Textbooks
With college textbooks costing over $1,000 a year for many students, soon-to-be sophomore Matt Schroeder has come up with a clever way to cut costs.
He developed a system for borrowing books from undergrads, offering them nominal compensation to delay selling them.
&quot;My Calculus textbook, which normally costs $180, I got a $10 semester and a Chick-fil-A cookie,&quot; says Schroeder, 19, who attends Covenant College in Georgia.
Required literature for last semester would cost $430, he says.
He spent $120.
The average student spends more than $1,200 a year on textbooks and supplies, according to the College Council, but students have a range of options to cut those costs.
Students are increasingly opting for online shopping and creative ideas like the Schroeder system.
Book rentals are becoming more and more popular, allowing students to use a book for a semester, and are often substantially cheaper than buying them.
Nibo, Inc., which owns more than 250 university bookstores, says book rentals have doubled since 2011.
Industry research shows that about a quarter of the books in university bookstores were borrowed during the past spring semester, says Nibo vice president Trevor Meyer.
Less than half of all books are purchased from university bookstores, according to the National Association of University Stores.
Here is an introductory course on the best ways to get a good deal.
Purchase in the online store
Sometimes, if you go online, the price of a new book can be one third of what you see in a university bookstore.
The ninth edition of Calculus by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards, and Robert Hostetler has a list price of about $290, but a new copy can be purchased for $239.99 from Chegg.com, which specializes in textbook sales.
Buying used
If you don&#39;t mind someone else&#39;s marks or damage, used textbooks are a good option.
Mathematical Analysis sells for $93.49 pre-owned on Chegg.com.
Matt Casaday, 25, a fourth-year student at Brigham Young University, says he paid 42 cents on Amazon.com for a used copy of Strategic Media Decisions: Understanding the Business Side of the Advertising Business.
The book was selling for $48 new.
Educators such as Ingrid Bracey, director of the College Without Walls at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, suggest that students check with their professors to see if previous editions can be used.
Sometimes updates are not essential to classes.
In such cases, older editions can often be found for a very small fraction of the cost of the latest edition.
Besides Chegg and Amazon, Half.com, owned by eBay Inc., is a popular alternative for buying used books.
rental
It&#39;s worth considering renting textbooks if you handle them well enough, don&#39;t forget to return them, and don&#39;t want to keep them after the course is over.
You can save over 80% on the cost of a new book.
For example, one student was able to rent Calculus for a semester for about $20.
Find out the rules of the store where you borrow books, including any fines you may be charged for marks, underlining, and damage.
If you rent a book, remember that if you do not return the book, the fines may even exceed the cost of a new copy.
E-books
E-books instead of traditional textbooks are another option.
Sometimes such books are actually rented by purchasing an electronic license for a certain period from distributors such as Amazon.com, Chegg and Barnes &amp; Noble Inc.
Renting Calculus on Chegg.com for six months will cost about $61.
Bracey says literature students can often find the best prices, as many classics can now be downloaded for free, while science and engineering literature can be quite expensive.
Regardless, take a look.
Joe Gault, 29, who is about to start at Pepperdine Law School, recommends using the ISBN to find out book prices, as this ensures you&#39;re looking for the exact text you&#39;re looking for.
Before ordering online, Gault says, be sure to check to see if the book is actually in stock.
This lesson was not easy for him.
The delivery of the book he had purchased was delayed by four weeks, and he ended up paying full price at the university bookstore.
