Why Guardians of the Galaxy Failed to Save the Box Office
Sylvester Stallone&#39;s The Expendables 3 returned less than $30 million from its $90 million budget in the US, while Sin City: A Dame to Kill For only returned $12 million from its $70 million budget.
Cameron Diaz&#39;s &quot;Home Video&quot; brought in only $14.6 million in its opening weekend, while children&#39;s films like How to Train Your Dragon 2 are also disappointing in revenue.
An article by Telegraph film critic Robbie Collin points out that when it comes to children&#39;s films, it may be the poor quality of the films themselves.
Collin called 2014 the &quot;worst&quot; year ever for children&#39;s films and called How to Train Your Dragon 2 a barely &quot;functioning&quot; fantasy sequel.
However, when it comes to films aimed at a somewhat older audience, it seems that the problem is not necessarily the quality of the films themselves.
In July, Entertainment Weekly compared the average CinemaScore and Metacritic ratings for each film with a summer release of at least 2,000 copies between the Memorial Day holiday in May and July 20 in 2013 and this year.
The results, which take into account the opinions of both moviegoers and film critics, suggest that this year&#39;s crop of films is similar in caliber to last year&#39;s hits.
Some commentators suggest that it may be due to changing viewing habits and the growing popularity of Internet streaming services such as Netflix.
Director Jon Favreau, who is currently working on the upcoming Disney film The Jungle Book, told the Hollywood Reporter: &quot;I think times are changing.&quot;
We must recognize this and not try to chase what was before.
In contrast to the current box office decline in Hollywood, Netflix&#39;s revenue from the streaming service hit $1.2 billion, nearly doubling last year&#39;s $837 million.
Last summer, director Steven Spielberg slammed studios for relying too much on comic book franchises and predicted the &quot;collapse&quot; of Hollywood.
In light of the current downturn, some commentators argue that there was some truth in his dire predictions.
With several potential box office hits set to release in the summer of 2015, including Avengers: Age of Ultron, Minions and Jurassic Park, others in the film industry are more optimistic.
X-Men producer Simon Kinberg recently called the box office drop &quot;cyclical,&quot; telling the Hollywood Reporter, &quot;Next summer will be the highest-grossing summer in history, and no one is going to worry about it.&quot;
Food sanctions do not scare the owners of establishments with Caucasian and Central Asian food, but Russian suppliers are a nightmare for European and Japanese restaurants.
And in general, public catering still prefers to replace prohibited imports with products not from Russia, but from Latin America, Israel and China.
&quot;It&#39;s better to eat lightly salted cucumber than bad mozzarella,&quot; Mariano Valerio, head chef of the Italian restaurant Barlotti, laments the quality of cheeses that suppliers offer him instead of Italian ones.
Mozzarella and burrata cheese ran out first in the restaurant, they have a short shelf life.
Stocks of parmesan should be enough for another couple of months.
What to do?
Switch to Russian?
In 2005 I was at the Dorogomilovsky market.
Mariano Valerio makes such eyes that it is clear: shocking memories do not let him go until now.
The meat was lying on carts just 30 centimeters from the floor!
There are cats!
Rats!
Then I said that we would never buy anything in Russian markets for our restaurant.
I don&#39;t know, maybe things have changed there now.
But the other day they brought me fish from the Far East for testing.
So she turned out to be rotten!
I said that I don&#39;t even want to talk to the person who brought it to us.
Valerio is surprised that many things that are usual for Italy are a curiosity for a Russian manufacturer.
A few years ago I was forced to buy Russian beef.
