Sanctions menu
On August 6, President Vladimir Putin signed a decree on the application of certain economic measures to ensure the security of Russia, which are mainly referred to as food sanctions.
It is forbidden to import beef, pork, poultry meat and offal, deli meats, fish, shellfish, milk, yogurt, cottage cheese, cheeses, vegetables, fruits, nuts, sausages and sugar syrups into the country.
Restaurants began to leapfrog with suppliers: food prices have risen, it is urgent to look for analogues from other countries.
This will have the strongest impact on expensive mono-cuisine restaurants in France, Italy, Spain, where food was supplied directly from the &quot;mother&quot; countries.
Public catering had to be rebuilt before.
For example, when at the beginning of 2014 the Rosselkhoznadzor banned the import of Australian beef, and a year earlier - American and Canadian meat.
In return, suppliers have established beef supplies from Argentina, Uruguay and New Zealand.
But the summer 2014 sanctions turned out to be much more severe.
True, on August 20, Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev approved amendments to a presidential decree that remove Atlantic salmon and trout fry, lactose-free milk, seed potatoes, sweet corn, peas and onions for sowing from the ban.
Valerio, an Italian, hopes that the sanctions can still be eased.
In the meantime, some restaurants exist in conditions of uncertainty.
According to Vostok-Zapad, one of the largest suppliers of HoReCa, the share of imported products in the premium segment was up to 70%.
&quot;Expensive restaurants will have to change their menus to match what local farmers and other countries produce,&quot; says Sergey Mironov, a restaurateur and owner of the Restconsult agency.
If the chef is strong, this will not be a problem for him.
Only we have very few such chefs, and it can take two or three months to develop a new menu.
Trigel from the Brasserie Most restaurant is ready for this: 10-15% of the dishes will have to be abandoned, another half of the menu will be reworked.
Mixed cuisine restaurants are already beginning to replace dishes, such as marbled beef steak, with beef stroganoff, Sergei Mironov says.
&quot;Cheese from Europe can be replaced by Russian, Belarusian cheeses, cheeses from Serbia, Argentina, Tunisia, Chile,&quot; says Oksana Glibchuk, a representative of the East-West company.
Cream and dairy products from Europe have analogues in Russia and Belarus.
Chicken from the USA can be replaced with chicken from Russia and Belarus, salmon and salmon from Norway - salmon, salmon, trout from Belarus and Chile.
The lack of vegetables and fruits of European production can be compensated for by the products of domestic producers, proposals from Serbia, Moldova and China.
According to Mironov, it will be easier for budget chain restaurants to reorganize than for the premium segment: it is unlikely that gourmets who can distinguish Italian mozzarella from Russian go there.
Although it will be difficult for the Ginza Project establishments, he believes.
Ginza Project has several dozen restaurants under different brands and with their own menus.
It will take a lot of time to replace it,&quot; says Mironov.
Ginza declined to comment, citing a lack of owners in the country.
The owners of cafes of Caucasian and Central Asian cuisine emphasize that products from the former Soviet republics are more fragrant than European ones.
But there are also quite a few restaurants that are practically unaffected by the sanctions.
These include establishments with the cuisine of the CIS countries: Georgian, Uzbek, Armenian and Azerbaijani.
&quot;There are no expensive products in Georgian cuisine,&quot; says Khatuna Kolbaya, owner of the Georgian restaurant Saperavi and the Wai Me! cafe.
All cheeses for us are made in Russia, many dishes are based on chicken fillet, we do not use exotic greens.&quot;
So far, not a single dish has been removed from the menu in Kolbai&#39;s establishments.
Timur Lansky, the owner of Chaihona N1 restaurants with Uzbek cuisine, is also not embarrassed by the sanctions: he will only have to exchange lamb for New Zealand.
If Russia arranges imports from Uzbekistan, Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan, we will even win in price, it will be cheaper for us than imports from Europe,” he says.
From the CIS, you can get tenderloin, lamb, tomatoes, cucumbers, and fruits cheaper.
At the same time, what is brought from Central Asia is much better than &quot;plastic&quot; from Italy, Spain and Turkey.
Everyone knows about Uzbek tomatoes that they are tasty and sweet.
Nobody talks about Spanish like that.
After the introduction of sanctions, the representative of the Ministry of Agriculture and Water Resources of Uzbekistan, Olimboy Artykov, said that he plans to double the export of fruits and vegetables to Russia by 2016.
Belarus and Kazakhstan announced their intention to replace European imports in Russia almost immediately after the imposition of sanctions.
Fast food restaurants that responded to Deneg&#39;s request also react quite calmly to the sanctions.
The press service of McDonald&#39;s said that localization exceeds 85% and the network works with 160 Russian suppliers.
According to Tatyana Bogdanova, head of the Subway Russia sourcing department, the chain buys about 80% of its products from Russia, although there may be temporary difficulties with the supply of vegetables and rising prices for meat products that are made from imported raw materials.
In &quot;Teremka&quot; &quot;sanctioned products&quot; in general took no more than 4%.
Sanctions did not affect the noodle &quot;Wokker&quot;.
KFC, Burger King and Kroshka Potato did not respond to Deneg&#39;s request, but other market participants claim that the degree of localization of Burger King is significantly less than that of McDonald&#39;s.
