From August 2, the payment limit under the &quot;Europrotocol&quot; is 50 thousand rubles, and from October 1 in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in the Moscow and Leningrad regions, it will be increased to 400 thousand rubles.
The bottom line is that often, even with minor damage, in a situation where an accident can be issued according to the &quot;European protocol&quot;, the drivers involved in the accident call the traffic police.
After all, if you had a hull insurance policy, it was impossible to get a refund on it without a certificate from the traffic police.
The parameters prescribed in the draft directive are precisely designed to eliminate this obstacle to the introduction of the &quot;Europrotocol&quot; in Russia.
According to them, the maximum hull insurance payment in connection with an accident, issued without traffic police officers, should not be lower than the limit according to the &quot;European protocol&quot;.
But at the same time, it cannot be higher than the limit specified in the hull insurance contract.
The idea is certainly useful and theoretically capable of unloading both traffic police officers and the road.
But, most likely, neither motorists nor insurers will be delighted with it.
The latter are already talking about a serious threat of an increase in fraud, which may lead to the introduction of new rules for Casco payments.
As for the drivers, it&#39;s hard to imagine what work will have to be done to overcome the primordial Russian conservatism.
The driver in most cases will wait for hours for the inspector to file a minor accident, because it is more reliable.
And it is still unknown what will be easier - to defeat the scammers or to convince drivers of the reliability of the &quot;European protocol&quot;.
The savings certificate will be made nominal and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates to the bearer, but it will allow banks to make them an analogue of an irrevocable deposit.
The Treasury is preparing a bill that will ban bearer savings certificates.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as the rates here are higher than for bank deposits.
The fact is that bearer savings certificates do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, since there is no need to make deductions to the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA) fund.
The piquancy of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which, according to the DIA, control 98% of the profile market, will suffer from it.
Moreover, the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the estimates of the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, they explain in the DIA, is that the clients of a small bank who have bought such a certificate, if their license is revoked, try to get money from the DIA.
Some savers, lacking sufficient financial literacy and buying bearer savings certificates, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified lack of insurance payments on these certificates in the event of a bank&#39;s license being revoked can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when holders of bearer certificates tried to collect insurance compensation through the courts,&quot; the DIA said.
The problem is, of course, illusory.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of certificates anyway, since they have no right to compensation from the state by law.
If the point were that the instrument was not insured in the DIA, metal accounts would be banned along with it, on which citizens&#39; funds are accounted for in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but so far no one encroaches on their existence.
The point, most likely, is that bearer certificates are a very convenient security, which can actually act as quasi-money.
At the same time, their movement is practically uncontrollable: any bank client can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before cashing out, such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the draft law stipulates that a savings certificate must be a registered security, which must be kept in a depository.
And to sweeten the pill for banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right to early redemption.
That is, an analogue of an irrevocable deposit is being introduced, which bankers have long dreamed of.
