Sinful boredom
The film by Frank Miller and Robert Rodriguez &quot;Sin City 2: A Dame to Kill For&quot; did not revolutionize at all what one could expect from it.
The first Sin City (2005), filmed with a minimal but symbolic contribution from Quentin Tarantino, revolutionized the relationship between film, comics and literary noir.
The sequel is also revolutionary in its own way: in the sense that it destroys the fundamental for modern thinking chain &quot;thesis - antithesis - synthesis&quot; (if we understand the universe of noir by thesis, and the cosmos of comics by antithesis).
From now on, it should be read: &quot;thesis - antithesis - chaos.&quot;
&quot;Sin City-2&quot; is chaotic both on a dramatic and philosophical level: both times it is chaotic in the bad sense of the word.
Yes, some of the characters are familiar from the first &quot;City&quot;, although, here, the thug Marv (Mickey Rourke), I remember, ended his life in the electric chair, but here, nothing, he just manages to grab - in the role of a kind of people&#39;s combatant - knives and other axes with nooses.
But the old men are literally pushed by the elbows of the newcomers, as if breaking into the city from some other film, the meaning and plot of which the audience is asked not to worry about.
So, its own story, shamelessly cut off by the authors at the most interesting place, the super-lucky player Johnny (Joseph Gordon-Levitt).
The lustfully frigid Eva Lord (Eva Green) and Dwight (Josh Brolin) who is avenging her for something have their own.
But this confusion, in which Dwight, say, cannot be distinguished by sight from Johnny - especially since the faces, like other parts of the body, are demolished with inexorable regularity - is not a problem, and not even half the trouble.
Well, these are not people, we understand that these are noir archetypes: a fatal bitch, an overly self-confident player, a detective who has fallen into the &quot;honey trap&quot; of sex, a corrupt senator ghoul.
Well, when the archetype waltzes with the archetype and drives the archetype, then this is no longer a movie, but read that abstract painting.
And asking abstract painting questions about the logic of the plot is simply ridiculous.
Besides, even in this hectic world, there is something constant.
The fighting whores from the first &quot;City&quot; still hold all-round defense against the forces of darkness besieging their native slums.
Yes, and the ghost of Detective Hartigan, no, no, and look at the light, and Bruce Willis is always a pleasure to look at.
The main problem of &quot;Sin City-2&quot; is different.
Frank Miller was good because, as a draftsman, he skillfully combined comics and noir, and as a director, he turned the idea of \u200b\u200bhow to transfer comics to the screen.
Comic and noir are two aggressively opposed &quot;realities&quot;.
The modern comic book phenomenon was born in the late 1920s, at the same time that Dashiell Hammett&#39;s novels Bloody Harvest (1929), The Maltese Falcon (1930) and The Glass Key (1931) created the canon of noir, then called hard -boiled school - &quot;cool school&quot;.
Or pulp fiction.
Comics gave Hollywood many dozens of heroes: from the sailor Popeye - a spinach devourer who gives him heroic strength, Superman, Batman and detective Dick Tracy to Hulk, Thor, Spider-Man and other &quot;avengers&quot;.
But in any movie based on comics, there was something flawed: drawn characters stubbornly did not want to acquire on-screen flesh, remained pretenders in the &quot;real&quot; world surrounding them willy-nilly.
Simply put, they were completely devoid of &quot;existence&quot;.
Noir, on the contrary, is the most existential genre of world literature.
After the world wars, the traditional novel - with experiences, characters, family scandals and historical background - lost all credibility.
What Forsytes, what Thibauts and Rougon-Makkars, what even Bolkonskys and Rostovs are generally conceivable after Verdun, Auschwitz and Hiroshima?
Such a novel peacefully mutated into the format of a soap opera, and a crime - that is, marginal by definition - novel rose to the level of philosophical prose.
Hammett learned the hard way what it is to work as an orderly at the front.
He was a communist.
As, by the way, such pillars of the genre as writers Horace McCoy and Jim Thompson, directors Jules Dassin, Joseph Losey, Edward Dmitrik were at least close to the Communist Party.
Therefore, noir, the archetype of which they set, is, firstly, rude and cynical, and secondly, purely social.
This is almost an American version of socialist realism.
The first &quot;Sin City&quot; was remarkable precisely because it unnaturally, but organically combined comics with noir.
For the first time on the screen, the comic came to life, not at all embarrassed by its graphic nature, and did not pretend to be a &quot;real&quot; movie.
The gloom of a venal world, where the cardinal ordered the murders and the senator covered for the monstrous sadistic son, was quite worthy of Hammett&#39;s pen.
And the picturesque details like severed heads with which the sadist decorated his nest, the pen of the brilliant James Ellroy, the author of The Black Orchid and the best - that is, declaratively nauseating - representative of neo-noir.
&quot;Sin City 2&quot; is not even a retreat, but a capitulation of the radical Miller-Rodriguez style to the comic book tradition.
Probably, in many respects this happened because of 3D technologies.
When you watch the second &quot;Sin City&quot;, you feel yourself enclosed in a glass ball, inside of which snow fills up a toy cesspool.
However, most often it is not snow, but bloody lumps, but by and large, what&#39;s the difference?
Well, there is nothing to say about sociality.
After all, it is possible only when somewhere, somewhere, sometimes, even on the side of a dirty swamp, there is a normal world where you can return a girl who has gone along a crooked path or, say, tell inconsolable parents that her destroyer is punished .
When in the city of sin there is no place for anything but sin, then sin is no longer a sin, but a norm.
Boring as usual.
The chaos of Sin City 2 is just boring.
In fairness, domestic rental gave this insipid sin a small, but peppercorn.
The credits warn that the film contains harmful smoking scenes.
In relation to the spectacle, in the very vegetarian episode of which a person&#39;s fingers are broken with tongs, this smacks of hellish humor.
Hammett would love it.
