In an interview with state-run Channel One, Putin denounced the Ukrainian military campaign to retake separatist-held territory in eastern Donetsk and Luhansk regions, which were seized in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently named the captured territories Novorossiya, or New Russia, a name that harks back to the pre-revolutionary glory days of the Russian Empire.
Putin said that anyone who believes that peace talks will happen in the near future, as Ukrainian politicians begin campaigning for parliamentary elections on October 26 and as government forces attack civilian settlements in separatist-held regions, is &quot;a prisoner of illusion.&quot; , reported ITAR-TASS.
&quot;We must immediately start meaningful negotiations, not only on technical issues, but also on the political structure of society and the state status of southeastern Ukraine, in order to serve the interests of the people living there,&quot; he said.
Peskov said Putin&#39;s words about statehood were meant in the context of a broader autonomy that had been discussed for months with leaders in Kiev in an attempt to assuage fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights were in danger.
Only the Ukrainian government can give the eastern regions the autonomy they need, Peskov said.
This is not a matter for discussion between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, &quot;because this is not a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but an internal Ukrainian conflict.&quot;
The intervention of a Kremlin spokesman to correct a &quot;misinterpretation&quot; of Putin&#39;s words underlined the decision of the Russian leadership to deal with the separatist uprising in the east in a different way than openly seizing Crimea, where the majority of the population of 2 million are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have to fight a much harder battle to annex even the Donetsk and Lugansk regions of eastern Ukraine, since most of its 6.5 million inhabitants are non-Russians, and pre-conflict polls showed widespread support for a desire to stay inside Ukraine.
The autonomy that Russian diplomats have been discussing in international forums would give regional governments in Ukraine the power to determine trade agreements and foreign policy themselves, essentially giving the Kremlin de facto control over the territory that would connect Russia&#39;s mainland to Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, annexed five months ago, is home to Russia&#39;s main navy, as well as commercial maritime institutions and historic seaside resorts.
The regions between Russia&#39;s Rostov Oblast and Crimea are also home to mines, factories, and foundries that produce essential equipment for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko suggested during his June 7 inaugural speech that Ukrainian lawmakers, after new elections, weigh constitutional amendments to give breakaway regions greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
