Anger is the most versatile and functional human emotion.
An angry facial expression is biologically universal for humanity, and each organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists from Australia and the USA have found out.
They described their findings in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in a press release from the University of California at Santa Barbara.
Angry facial expressions — brows drawn in and down, lips stretched into a thin line, nostrils flared — are the same across cultures, and even blind children who have never seen them make them, said Aaron Sell, lead author of the study.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion has evolved to effectively handle disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his terms, and he conveys this to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers found confirmation of their other hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and turn to assault, consider themselves entitled to impose unfavorable conditions on others, and also prefer forceful methods of conflict resolution to peaceful ones.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily a &quot;bargaining emotion&quot;, the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create an angry facial expression should make the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thereby force them to agree as soon as possible. with its terms to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated faces with or without each of the seven elements of the angry face on a computer and showed them to informants.
Although lowered eyebrows or a protruding chin alone did not make the face angry, the participants in the study unanimously recognized the person depicted with such features as physically stronger.
Human anger, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one&#39;s own strength, forcing one to agree and obey.
A man flares his nostrils and purses his lips for the same purpose as a frog that puffs up or a baboon that shows off its fangs.
“Anger is triggered by the interlocutor’s refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes on a form that most effectively demonstrates to the opposite side the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,&quot; said anthropologist John Tooby.
